            <div class="col-md-10 mx-auto">
                <!-- HTML Introduction -->
                <div class="card shadow rounded">
                    <div class="card-body">
                        <h2 class="text-primary">HTML Introduction</h2>
                        <p class="lead">HTML is the standard markup language for creating Web pages.</p>
                        <ul class="list-unstyled">
                            <li><b>HTML</b> stands for <b>Hyper Text Markup Language</b>.</li>
                            <li>It provides the structure of a Web page.</li>
                            <li>HTML elements are the building blocks of web pages.</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <!-- Basic HTML Structure -->
                <div class="card mt-3 shadow rounded">
                    <div class="card-body">
                    <h2 class="text-secondary">HTML Example</h2>
                        <p class="lead">HTML is the standard markup language for creating web pages.</p>
                        <h5 class="mt-3">Basic HTML Structure:</h5>
                        <pre><code>&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;
&lt;html&gt;
    &lt;head&gt;
        &lt;title&gt;Web page title&lt;/title&gt;
    &lt;/head&gt;
    &lt;body&gt;
        &lt;h1&gt;Write Your First Heading&lt;/h1&gt;
        &lt;p&gt;Write Your First Paragraph.&lt;/p&gt;
    &lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;
                    </code></pre>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <!-- Example Explanation -->
                <div class="card mt-3 shadow rounded">
                    <div class="card-body">
                    <h2 class="text-secondary">Example Explanation</h2>
                        <p class="lead">HTML is used to create web pages.</p>
                        <ul class="list-unstyled">
                            <li>The <code>&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;</code> tells the browser that this is an <strong>HTML5 document</strong>.</li>
                            <li>The <code>&lt;html&gt;</code> tag is the <strong>main container</strong> for the webpage.</li>
                            <li>The <code>&lt;head&gt;</code> tag holds <strong>important information</strong> like the page title and styles.</li>
                            <li>The <code>&lt;title&gt;</code> tag sets the <strong>page title</strong>, shown in the browser tab.</li>
                            <li>The <code>&lt;body&gt;</code> tag contains <strong>everything you see</strong> on the page, like text, images, and links.</li>
                            <li>The <code>&lt;h1&gt;</code> tag creates a <strong>big heading</strong>.</li>
                            <li>The <code>&lt;p&gt;</code> tag creates a <strong>paragraph</strong>.</li>
                        </ul>
                        <h5 class="mt-4">What is an HTML Element?</h5>
                        <p>An HTML element has an opening tag, some content, and a closing tag:</p>
                        <pre><code>&lt;tagname&gt; Content here... &lt;/tagname&gt;</code></pre>
                        <p>An element includes everything from the opening tag to the closing tag. Here’s an example:</p>
                        <pre><code>&lt;h1&gt;Hello World&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This is a paragraph.&lt;/p&gt;</code></pre>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

   




